'''Muraya-niimasu-Mifutsuhime Shrine''' (むらやにいますみふつひめじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Shiki District|Q1155036|qid=Q1155036|1=Shiki District, Nara}}{{ill|lt=Tawaramoto Town|Q1203159|qid=Q1203159|1=Tawaramoto, Nara}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha (major shrine)|Q134917288|qid=Q134917288|1=Shikinai Taisha}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}. The shrine stands facing the “Nakatsu-michi” (Tachibana Highway), one of the {{ill|lt=ancient roads of Yamato|Q11433382|qid=Q11433382|lt=Three Yamato Roads|1=Three Yamato Roads}}.

The principal enshrined deity is {{ill|lt=Miho-tsu-hime|Q6378698|qid=Q6378698|lt=Miho-tsu-hime no Mikoto|1=Mihotsuhime-no-Mikoto}} (also known as Mifutsuhime-gami), with {{ill|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi no Mikoto|1=Ōmononushi}} enshrined as an accompanying deity. Miho-tsu-hime no Mikoto is the consort deity of {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi no Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}, and in the myths recorded in the *Kojiki* and *Nihon Shoki*, Ōmononushi and Ōkuninushi are regarded as the same deity. Ōmononushi no Mikoto is the enshrined deity of {{ill|lt=Ōmiwa Shrine|Q705542|qid=Q705542|1=Ōmiwa Shrine}}, and this shrine, which enshrines his consort deity, is considered a branch shrine of Ōmiwa Shrine.

===History===
=== Overview ===
The date of the shrine’s founding is unknown. According to the *{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}*, during the {{ill|lt=Jinshin War|Q2378252|qid=Q2378252|1=Jinshin War}} in the first year of {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenmu|Q335181|qid=Q335181|1=Emperor Tenmu}}’s reign ({{ill|lt=673|Q31105|qid=Q31105|1=673}}), the Muraya deity delivered a {{ill|lt=divine oracle|Q217123|qid=Q217123|1=Oracle}} to {{ill|lt=Ōtomo no Fukei|Q11432333|qid=Q11432333|1=Ōtomo no Fukei}}, who was on the side of Prince Ōama, saying, “The enemy is coming, so block the Nakatsu-michi.” In recognition of this service, a {{ill|lt=divine rank|Q11591025|qid=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} was conferred upon the deity. This is the earliest recorded instance of the bestowal of a divine rank. Records such as the Yamato Province Tax Register ({{ill|lt=Shōsōin documents|Q11545362|qid=Q11545362|1=Shōsōin Documents}}) and the {{ill|lt=Shinshōkyakuchokufu-shō|Q11502312|qid=Q11502312|1=Shinshō Kyakuchokufushō}} note that the imperial court made repeated donations of {{ill|lt=shrine estates|Q1689534|qid=Q1689534|1=Shinpo}} to the shrine. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, the shrine is listed as a major shrine and is recorded as receiving offerings at the Tsukinami, Aename, and Niiname festivals.

In Shōwa 2 ({{ill|lt=1926|Q5259|qid=Q5259|1=1926}}), the shrine was elevated to the rank of prefectural shrine.

{{quotation|
'''“Emperor Tenmu, Upper Volume,” *Nihon Shoki, Lower Volume*, Kodansha Academic Library'''<br/>
“Then the deity Muraya (Moriya Shrine) possessed the priest (shinkan) and said, ‘An army will come along the road within my shrine grounds. Therefore, block the shrine road.’”
}}

=== Divine Ranks ===
* {{ill|lt=Ten’an (Japanese era)|Q1075611|qid=Q1075611|lt=Ten’an|1=Ten'an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|qid=Q23897|1=859}}) {{ill|lt=January 27|Q2284|qid=Q2284|1=January 27}}: Promoted from Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade to Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade (*{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}*) – Recorded as “Muraya Nifutsuhime-gami.”

